      <body>
         <pb n="248"/>
         <milestone n="248" unit="page"/>
         <lb/>
         <head>NOTES <hi rend="small">TO THE </hi> POEM <hi rend="small">OF</hi> THE
                                   BROTHERS.<lb/>
            <hi rend="small">
               <lb/>note i. </hi>
         </head>
         <div xml:id="note1b">
            <p rend="note">Page 27—line 1. “There were two springs
                                   which bub-<lb/>bled side by side.” The impressive
                                   circumstance here de-<lb/>scribed, actually took place some years
                                   ago in this country, <lb/>upon an eminence called Kidstow Pike,
                                   one of the highest <lb/>of the mountains that surround
                                   Hawes-water. The sum-<lb/>mit of the Pike was stricken by
                                   lightning; and every trace <lb/>of one of the fountains
                                   disappeared, while the other con-<lb/>tinued to flow as
                                   before.</p>
         </div>
         <div xml:id="note2b">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">note ii.</hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note">Page 29—line 6. “The thought of death sits
                                   easy on the <lb/>man,” &amp;c. There is not any thing more
                                   worthy of remark <lb/>in the manners of the inhabitants of these
                                   mountains, than <lb/>the tranquillity, I might say indifference,
                                   with which they <lb/>think and talk upon the subject of death.
                                   Some of the <lb/>country church-yards, as here described, do not
                                   contain a <lb/>single tomb-stone, and most of them have a very
                                   small <lb/>number.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
